  footnotes: []
english:
  title: At the Gongbuk Pavilion in Cheongju
  author: Yu Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ascending the northern tower on this day of revelry,
    We witness the dawn of Dongkuk's restoration.
    Great deeds shall be passed down to ages yet unborn—
    I am compelled to inscribe these verses anew.

    Banners and flags rise thick along the road,
    While robes of state hover high in the void.
    Though this place claims joy enough,
    Songak Mountain calls to us still, waiting.
  footnotes:
    - Dongkuk (東國) refers to Korea, literally meaning 'Eastern Country.'
    - Songak Mountain (松山) alludes to Gaeseong, the capital of Goryeo, suggesting nostalgia or reflection on Korea's historical continuity.
    - The contrast between the celebration at Gongbuk Pavilion and the distant call of Songak Mountain reflects the poet's meditation on transience and duty.
